Show HN: I made an open site that links random resources for art practice
text:
Hi HN,

I built a site where you can find links to drawing references, sorted by topic (e.g. hands, people, cars, ...). Clicking on a link opens a random resource.

You can check out the site here: https://inspirationbot.art/versions/collage/main.html

I know HN isn't an art community, but since one aim of the project was to keep it as vanilla and plain as possible (HTML & CSS, no frameworks, no backend as such) I thought it may be of interest.

Another intent of the project is to use it to try out different web design styles, so if the link above is a bit too gaudy for your taste, you may enjoy the plain HTML version: https://inspirationbot.art/versions/plainhtml/main.html

The project is also open source (as well as free, no sign-up, no ads), see repo here: https://github.com/koljapluemer/inspirationbot

This is the first time I am trying to properly open source something (as opposed to code-dumping on GH), so: Please tell me what you think; technical feedback and any input in regards to the open source part is especially welcome.

Thanks!

title: The Trolley Problem Is All Too Real
On Simulated Companionship
Did I ruin my career?
text:
I've spent the past year as a technical product manager (role also allowed me to keep some eng work as a product eng as well). The company folded due to market conditions and I was laid off.

For the three years prior to that I was a full-time SWE. Initially at Amazon out of college but my team was cut after 8mo. , had a very strong streak and got promoted at my next gig at a startup (worked there for 1.8 years). That was followed by an 8mo. stint at another startup which happened to be an awful fit. Fortunately I had a full year as a TPM, but I can't help but feel like I've completely screwed myself.

I'm not exactly "senior" yet as an SWE or TPM and while I'm glad I've had a fair bit of experiences I feel very lost relative to friends who are working on startups or have established careers at larger tech companies.

Fortunately, I have plenty of runway (this might be a bad thing since clearly I need to change some patterns in my life). Obviously the market is bad, but given my relatively weak network I'm legitimately starting to lose hope. Previously, I'd at least get initial interviews, at this point I'm just getting rejection after rejection.

Is anyone else having a rough time with the current market?

title: Thinking Outside the Box: A Misguided Idea
Ask HN: How will social media change in the next years?
text:
BeReal, Discord, Snapchat, these are companies that are shaping the next generation of social, at least in my opinion. BeReal with authenticity, Discord with letting you join servers you like, Snapchat with letting you connect with your friends and give you an array of creative tools. I THINK the future of social media will be more private. Messaging is the new social IMO. The current big social platforms are entertainment platforms now, you don't even see anything from your friends.

So I think the change in social will be that people will want to join private spaces to talk with their friends, or with like-minded people. Do you also agree?

I'd love to hear your opinions.

Show HN: Historical HN Hiring Data
text:
Hi HN! A few days ago I saw a graph[0] that showed the # of job postings on HN was declining. I started wondering what other trends I could glean from the data, so I created this!

You can filter through the top level comments by keyword; for example you can filter by "remote" to see the massive spike around March 2020. Another interesting thing I found is that I can compare hiring across cities.

I hope you enjoy! I made it so that the links to your search are sharable so if you have some interesting data you should be able to just link the page you're on!

[0] https://rinzewind.org/blog-en/2023/the-tech-downturn-seen-th...
